photo_desc: A tiny little village on the outskirts of Nagano Prefecture. A humble and hardworking village with a high sense of community and belonging. Distinct season changes are common, often when the cherry blossom season comes, there is still snowfall from the previous season, covering the blossoms in white powdery snow. In the winter, it is busy and bustling, people have arrived from all over the world to ski and snowboard in this ski Olympic village. In the summer, it is so hot, it becomes almost unbearable to be outside. A lot of old people, old buildings, old architecture, old shrines, and old values and customs.
photo_mean: I took this photo after a season working in the village. The winter season had ended and it was nice enough weather that I could venture out of the village and see the village that had consumed me for many months in all its glory without being completely covered in white powder. The people that live here, became family. This village became home, more so during a period where getting home was impossible (C-19). As a young adult who is still growing, learning, and maturing every day, who I have become today and what I aspire to become is a testament to what I experienced here.

photo_desc: This is the forest near my house. It is a well hidden patch of native forest which is not well known to anyone. It is right near the city and the suburbs, but is tucked away down a gulley in the hills, so you can't see it from the street. The forest is peaceful and sheltered, and captures the sunlight. Because it is so secret I do not often meet people down there, which is what I love about it. I take my big dog, which makes me feel safe. But the forest always feels like home. The big trees tower over and make a canopy like a roof, protecting me from the elements. The ground is covered in soft dirt and fallen leaves, I like to walk barefoot. It smells so fresh and amazing, and there are fresh water streams which run through it. There are tracks which are maintained by a small group of people dedicated to this area. This forest has important historical significance as it was involved in the new zealand land wars, and was used by Maori and Pakeha. There are many special little tracks to explore, some very old and some newer ones. People who maintain this area make sure to preserve it and have fun making secret little places, like picnic areas for people to find. There is a historical Maori Pa site which is a beautiful and secluded spot I spend a lot of time. During covid this place became much more discovered and use by locals, which I didn't like. I know that sounds selfish, it does not belong to me but to everyone, but the seclusion of this place is partly why its so special. I like to come here with all my feelings and not feel the need to hide anything, so I have often come here to cry or stomp around angrily. I can lie down if I'm sleepy or explore and have fun if I'm happy. Take photos or videos if I'm feeling creative.
photo_mean: It shows how the trees reach up and create a beautiful canopy which the sun shines through. The place feels like a magical, peaceful world away, somewhere I can escape and feel free to be myself.

photo_desc:
This photo show's my dad's 'farm' (which isn't really a farm, that's just what we call it!)

It shows a green paddock with yellow dandelions dotted throughout, with a gully of trees to the left, and hills in the distance. It is cloudy but not dark, and there are a couple of blue-ish hay bails dotted around, too.

This is a photo of one of the three paddocks of my dad's 'farm'. It's not really a farm, that's just what we call it, it's more of a lifestyle block. I have basically grown up on this farm - dad is a horticulturist and this whole farm has been his big project since before I was born (he must be verging on having this for 30 years now!) 

I have spent nearly every Christmas, and many birthdays or just summer days at the farm, making it a special place for me, as it is full of fond memories. Dad has just planted an orchard in the other gully with every species of fruit you can imagine, and it is absolutely incredible, and Mum and Dad have just bought an old, run-down Church to put on this land, which they are going to do up and use it as a sort of retreat house of sorts.
